<rss version="2.0"><channel><title>守护者</title><description>卫报全文RSS。获取更多全文RSS：https://feedx.net</description><link/> https://theguardian.com <item><title><![CDATA[Lucy Letby to face retrial on charge of trying to murder baby girl, court told]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/sep/25/lucy-letby-retrial]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-25T10:32:24Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/6be9ca6bde79c452663ceb2beed45c74fdbb9e10/0_1078_2610_1566 /master/2610.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=012f683c07a84e19e7ee318897c26d05&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;露西·莱比。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;露西·莱比将面临重审，罪名是企图谋杀一名法庭获悉，这名 33 岁的前护士于 8 月被判有罪，罪名是在英格兰西北部的切斯特伯爵夫人医院谋杀了 7 名婴儿，并试图杀害另外 6 名婴儿。 .&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;陪审团无法对另外六项谋杀未遂罪作出裁决，这些罪名涉及三名新生女婴和两名男婴。她被指控两次试图杀死其中一个婴儿。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;检察官尼克·约翰逊 KC 周一告诉曼彻斯特皇家法院，检方将就其中一项指控重审莱比，即企图谋杀一名女婴。 2016 年 2 月 - 但不适用于其余罪名。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;法官 Goss KC 表示，由于法院“积压了大量案件”，新审判的第一个可用日期是 2024 年 6 月 10 日。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; >; &lt;p>;但是，他表示，在法官决定是否允许莱比对第一次审判的定罪提出上诉之前，不应进行任何新的审判。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;莱比将在在被判处多项终身监禁（每项罪名一项）后入狱，成为英国历史上第四位被判处此类刑罚的女性。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;莱比拒绝出席宣判和最后几天的庭审。她的审判通过西约克郡韦克菲尔德附近的 HMP New Hall 监狱会议室的视频链接观看了整个过程。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;坐在一张桌子旁，手里拿着一杯水和一卷卫生纸，她向法庭确认了自己的名字，并且她可以听到法律讨论。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 25 Sep 2023 18:52:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[British hiker found dead in Switzerland three months after going missing]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/25/british-hiker-aidan-roche-found-dead-switzerland-alps]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-25T10:43:57Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/19366c987b8ef7462df86bb8f490873c3f43cb51/0_74_739_443 /master/739.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=263fbf5404ce9a792be08e7eb14aabc8&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Aidan Roche&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;瑞士警方发现了一名失踪的英国徒步旅行者的尸体三个月后，他的家人证实了这一点。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Aidan Roche，29 岁，来自米德尔斯堡的一名海上化学工程师，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/03/英国徒步旅行者在瑞士失踪的家庭疯狂求生故事&quot;>;最后一次听到消息是在 6 月 22 日&lt;/a>;，当时正在瑞士阿尔卑斯山格林德瓦​​地区的艾格峰小道上徒步旅行，距离伯尔尼约 50 英里（80 公里）。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他的兄弟 Connor Roche &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/connor.roche.10&quot;>;说他的家人上周被告知&lt;/a>; 警察在小道附近发现了艾丹的尸体。他说：“这个消息对我们所有人都造成了沉重打击，尽管我们在过去几个月里一直在考虑这个结果。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我谨代表我的整个家庭向大家表示衷心的感谢谁帮助我们度过了这一切。这么多人的倾注支持帮助我们度过了所有的不确定性和痛苦，并显示了艾丹是多么受人爱戴。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“对于所有支持的信息，请在网上分享艾丹的照片和海报，以及帮助寻找他的捐款，我们对你们表示最深切的谢意。所有这些都有助于他回到我们身边。非常感谢。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;罗奇正在为期两周的露营旅行的第 12 天，据信他失踪时正在参观冰川后走回他的大篷车。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;一项筹款活动筹集了近 32,000 英镑，用于支付广告活动费用，以帮助瑞士当局在搜寻中找到新的线索。它还帮助支付搜索队使用直升机的费用。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;亲戚和朋友分享了他最后的视频，希望有人能认出与他在一起的人。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他的朋友贝丝·泰勒说：“他永远不会就这样消失。正常情况下，他每天都会与朋友和家人联系，分享图片或视频。我们是一大群非常亲密的朋友中的一员 - 他不会随机失踪。”&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 25 Sep 2023 18:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Officials detained as Libya awaits inquiry into deadly floods]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/25/libya-floods-officials-detained-derna]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-25T09:44:32Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/0194026838dc8a652cfe7b6e12f7669203cae7ad/0_97_3500_2100 /master/3500.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=86825a696919b4b0197ce4677b463bfc&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;救援人员在德尔纳洪水过后继续搜寻尸体&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;利比亚首席检察官已下令拘留八名现任和前任官员，等待他对本月早些时候两座大坝垮塌的调查，这场灾难导致数米高的水墙穿过沿海城市中心，造成数千人死亡。&lt;/p >; &lt;p>;德尔纳市外的两座水坝在被丹尼尔风暴淹没后于 9 月 11 日溃决，风暴给利比亚东部带来了大雨。官员们表示，这些建筑的倒塌淹没了该市四分之一的地区，摧毁了整个社区，并将人们卷入大海。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;政府官员和援助机构估计死亡人数从4,000 至超过 11,000。据搜索小组称，许多遇难者的尸体仍埋在废墟下或在地中海中。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;检察官周日表示，总检察长办公室 Al-Sidiq al-Sour 发表声明称询问了水资源管理局和水坝管理局的七名前任和现任官员，指控其管理不善、疏忽和错误导致了这场灾难。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2023/sep/25/libyans-after-devastating-floods-photo-essay&quot;>;利比亚人在毁灭性洪水后收拾残局——图片文章&lt;/a>;&lt; /p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;声明称，灾难后被解雇的德尔纳市市长阿卜杜勒-莫奈姆·盖蒂也受到了讯问。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;检察官下令将这八人带走。声明补充说，他们已被监禁，等待调查。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这些水坝是由一家南斯拉夫建筑公司于 20 世纪 70 年代在分割城市的河谷德尔纳河上方建造的。它们的目的是保护城市免受山洪爆发的影响，这种情况在该地区并不罕见。尽管科学家警告它们可能会决堤，但这些水坝几十年来都没有得到维护。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;一家国营审计机构 2021 年的一份报告称，尽管拨款超过 2 美元，但两座水坝仍未得到维护。 2012-13 年为此目的投资了 100 万英镑（160 万英镑）。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;一家土耳其公司于 2007 年签订合同，负责对两座大坝进行维护，并在两座大坝之间建造第三座大坝。该公司 Arsel Construction Company. 在其网站上表示，已于 2012 年 11 月完成工作。该公司没有回复寻求进一步评论的电子邮件。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;灾难发生两周后，当地和国际团队仍在泥土和空心建筑物中挖掘寻找尸体。他们还在德尔纳附近的地中海地区搜寻被洪水冲走的尸体。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;据联合国人道主义协调办公室称，洪水已导致德尔纳多达三分之一的住房和基础设施遭到破坏。事务（人道协调厅）。人道协调厅表示，当局已疏散该市受影响最严重的地区，只留下搜索和救护队。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;世界卫生组织表示，已登记死亡人数超过 4,000 人，其中包括外国人，但此前的死亡人数为利比亚红新月会负责人称这一数字为 11,300。人道协调厅表示，至少仍有 9,000 人失踪。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;风暴袭击了利比亚东部的其他地区，包括贝达、苏萨、马尔吉和沙哈特等城镇。该地区有数万人流离失所，并在学校和其他政府建筑中避难。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;对官员的讯问和可能的监禁是首席检察官在调查中迈出的关键的第一步。由于国家多年的分裂，利比亚很可能面临严峻的挑战。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;自2014年以来，利比亚东部一直处于哈利法·哈夫塔尔将军及其自封的利比亚国民军的控制之下。总部位于首都的黎波里的敌对政府控制着大部分国家资金并监督基础设施项目。两者都不容忍异议。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;总部位于的黎波里的咨询机构最高国务委员会呼吁进行彻底的国际调查，呼应全国许多居民的呼吁，反映出许多人对国家机构的深深不信任.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 25 Sep 2023 17:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[US urged to withhold military aid to Egypt in wake of Bob Menendez charges]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/25/us-urged-to-withhold-military-aid-to-egypt-in-wake-of-bob-menendez-charges]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-25T07:00:20Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/86a30baf8ec8e233c73c4912bbf80c8a2b04168d/0_53_4554_2733 /master/4554.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=34da2f5501d89b7534aee2a93b9c54a7&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;参议员鲍勃·梅嫩德斯乘电梯&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;参议员鲍勃·梅嫩德斯被指控腐败援助埃及政府为美国议员在一周内再次施压，要求他们停止对埃及提供军事援助奠定了基础。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;梅嫩德斯周五暂时辞去参议院外交关系委员会主席职务。是 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/23989458-united-states-of-america-v-robert-menendez-nadine-menendez-wael-hana-jose-uribe-and-fred- daibes&quot;>;被纽约南部地区法院起诉&lt;/a>;，提出一系列爆炸性且详细的指控。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;其中包括接受数十万美元的贿赂以及金条、抵押贷款付款以及包括一辆豪华汽车在内的礼物，以换取利用他的影响力并“以有利于埃及政府的方式”违反他的职责，同时支持其新泽西地区的清真肉类认证业务&lt;a href=&quot;https:// www.madamasr.com/en/2019/12/29/feature/economy/how-the-multi-million-dollar-business-of-certifying-halal-meat-imports-was-monopolized/&quot;>;链接到埃及州&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;参议员一再否认有任何不当行为，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/22/robert-menendez- democrats-quit-senate&quot;>;声明&lt;/a>;“那些相信正义的人相信无罪，直到被证明有罪”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;起诉书还详细说明了参议员与埃及情报部门成员的密切关系，包括拜登政府最近在华盛顿和开罗的办公室举行会议，讨论美国每年向埃及提供 13 亿美元的外国军事援助，而梅嫩德斯由于其职位而对该领域拥有实质性控制权。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;拜登政府最近以人权问题为由，选择扣留对埃及 8500 万美元的军事援助，大大低于前几年的扣留金额。此举引发了观察家的批评，他们指出埃及糟糕的人权记录，并指出埃及总统阿卜杜勒-法塔赫·塞西领导下的数万人被拘留，其中包括政治犯和&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/ aug/16/egypt-academic-salah-soltan-biden-detention&quot;>;美国绿卡持有者&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;距离本财政年度结束仅剩一周，梅南德斯的起诉引发了愤怒华盛顿的人权组织和游说者呼吁美国立法者以国家安全为由暂缓向埃及提供 2.35 亿美元的军事援助，这笔援助此前已于本月早些时候获得拜登政府批准。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“据三人称-根据起诉书，梅南德斯在为自己谋取利益的同时，利用自己的职位优先考虑埃及腐败和残暴的政府和安全部门的需求，”总部位于华盛顿的自由倡议组织表示，该组织专注于中东地区被关押的政治犯。 p>; &lt;p>;“起诉书指控埃及政府做出重大努力，以不当影响美国的政策和法律。拜登总统和他的政府应该要求埃及政府进行核算，并宣布对双边关系进行审查。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;华盛顿中东民主项目的宣传主任赛斯·宾德 (Seth Binder) 表示，他的组织将鉴于梅南德斯参议员的指控以及埃及干涉美国政策的消息，敦促立法者停止向埃及提供军事援助。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;国会这样介入并不常见。但起诉书中的信息也很不寻常，”他说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他补充道：“我们经常听说，使用军事援助作为杠杆是行不通的，因为埃及政府并不真正关心的援助。这份起诉书应该平息这一论点，它显然已被证明是错误的。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;针对梅嫩德斯的起诉书中的细节包括给他的妻子纳丁·梅嫩德斯 (Nadine Menendez) 的短信，这些短信被转交给了埃及官员，指定有关美国驻开罗大使馆工作人员的敏感信息。这些指控还包括梅嫩德斯通过他的妻子与埃及官员沟通，关于他个人批准向埃及出售特定武器的例子。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“询问大使馆工作人员的姓名和人员：这部分确实是可耻的在我看来，”宾德说。 “我们知道埃及经常试图骚扰在外国大使馆工作的埃及国民，利用他们收集情报和信息。参与其中确实是肮脏的。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;针对梅嫩德斯的广泛指控似乎可能会影响美国外交政策的多个领域，同时也让那些拥有&lt;a href=&quot;https://www .theguardian.com/global-development/2021/jun/08/biden-accused-of-u-turn-over-egypts- human-rights-abuses&quot;>;长期抱怨拜登政府在埃及问题上违背承诺&lt;/a>; 。作为候选人，拜登曾向塞西承诺“不开空白支票”，但他上任后与塞西的关系日益升温，事实证明了这一点。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 25 Sep 2023 15:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Thousands of refugees flee to Armenia in wake of Azerbaijan’s Nagorno-Karabakh military offensive – live]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2023/sep/25/refugees-armenia-nagorno-karabakh-azerbaijan-live]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-25T07:19:30Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/e5ca47b6928075c30ac51aab9f3ec3467e2b498a/0_235_5155_3093 /master/5155.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=4a959e4f0e24af80d3e3b172f02d3656&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;逃离家园的纳戈尔诺-卡拉巴赫亚美尼亚人被送上巴士，撤离到科尔尼佐尔人道主义中心的戈里斯，亚美尼亚。&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 25 Sep 2023 15:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Nagorno-Karabakh: refugees pour into Armenia after military offensive]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/25/nagorno-karabakh-refugees-pour-into-armenia-after-military-offensive-azerbaijan]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-25T06:30:43Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/4d5bb1087e4bfa21eec485f5b17b86bac3c5cd0a/0_303_6048_3628 /master/6048.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=85b658a73ee3f5bf8b298d1ba43f3043&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;在阿塞拜疆的军事行动后，亚美尼亚居民离开纳戈尔诺-卡拉巴赫的斯捷潘纳克特。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;几乎继上周的&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/20/nagorno-karabakh-death-toll-azerbaijan-亚美尼亚-攻击-冲突-俄罗斯-美国&quot;>;阿塞拜疆在争议地区发动军事攻势，造成数百人死亡、受伤或失踪。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;截至当地时间周一凌晨 5 点，超过据俄罗斯塔斯社援引亚美尼亚政府声明称，已有 2,900 名难民抵达亚美尼亚。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;数百名难民开始&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023 /sep/24/first-evacuees-from-nagorno-karabakh-cross-into-armenia-azerbaijan&quot;>;周日从纳戈尔诺-卡拉巴赫穿越&lt;/a>;，成为近一年来第一批抵达亚美尼亚并团聚的平民阿塞拜疆实施了长达 10 个月的封锁，导致当地首都斯捷潘纳克特及周边地区的食品、燃料和水严重短缺。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该地区分离的亚美尼亚政府官员表示他们计划将数千名流离失所者从该地区疏散到&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/world/armenia&quot;>;亚美尼亚&lt;/a>;。&lt;/ p>; &lt;p>;当地政府表示，俄罗斯维和人员将陪同撤离人员从争议地区越过边境进入亚美尼亚。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot; https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/22/i-came-to-apologise-armenian-relatives-visit-soldiers-graves-after-ceasefire-deal&quot;>;“我是来道歉的”：停火协议后，亚美尼亚亲属前往扫墓&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“亲爱的同胞们，我们谨通知您，在俄罗斯维和人员的陪同下，亚美尼亚无家可归的家庭一份声明称，“政府将在不久的将来发布有关其他人口群体搬迁的信息。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“政府将在不久的将来发布有关其他人口群体重新安置的信息。”亚美尼亚总理尼科尔·帕希尼扬周日在现场讲话中表示：“我们的政府将热烈欢迎来自纳戈尔诺-卡拉巴赫的兄弟姐妹。纳戈尔诺-卡拉巴赫的亚美尼亚人仍然面临种族清洗的危险。人道主义物资已于近日抵达纳戈尔诺-卡拉巴赫，但这并没有改变局势。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“如果不为纳戈尔诺-卡拉巴赫的亚美尼亚人创造真正的生活条件，以及有效的保护机制，如果反对种族清洗，那么纳戈尔诺-卡拉巴赫的亚美尼亚人将被驱逐出家园视为唯一出路的可能性就会增加。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;纳戈尔诺-卡拉巴赫的亚美尼亚人——国际公认的领土的一部分阿塞拜疆此前超出其控制范围，上周在规模大得多的阿塞拜疆军队进行了 24 小时的军事行动后被迫停火。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;亚美尼亚和阿塞拜疆在 30 年来为这片飞地发生了两场战争 -阿塞拜疆在 2020 年为期六周的冲突中收复纳戈尔诺-卡拉巴赫及其周边地区的大片领土。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安将于周一会见阿塞拜疆总统伊利哈姆·阿利耶夫，讨论上周，阿利耶夫的盟友埃尔多安在 2020 年冲突中为阿塞拜疆提供了武器支持，他上周表示，他支持阿塞拜疆最新军事行动的目标，但没有参与其中。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;亚美尼亚称上周的行动造成 200 多人死亡、400 人受伤，此举遭到美国和亚美尼亚其他西方盟友的谴责。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;周日，阿塞拜疆国防部表示已没收​​了更多物品亚美尼亚分裂分子的军事装备，包括火箭、炮弹、地雷和弹药。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;纳戈尔诺-卡拉巴赫的亚美尼亚人不接受阿塞拜疆在该地区一体化过程中保障其权利的承诺。亚美尼亚呼吁立即部署联合国特派团，以监测该地区的人权和安全。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“百分之九十九点九的人宁愿离开我们的历史土地，”亚美尼亚顾问戴维·巴巴扬 (David Babayan) 说道。脱离国家（也称为阿尔扎赫）的总统萨姆维尔·沙赫拉曼扬 (Samvel Shahramanyan) 告诉路透社。&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https:// feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange “ target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 25 Sep 2023 14:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[China drastically cuts seafood imports from Japan in wake of Fukushima water release]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/25/china-drastically-cuts-seafood-imports-from-japan-in-wake-of-fukushima-water-release]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-25T05:46:00Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/7ca0ec878e13a9954500b4184f74974798aa0e6b/0_283_4242_2545 /master/4242.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=90ad10766cb11645c78538717f9f4abb&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;滨站鱼市场和美食广场看到来自福岛县的海鲜&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;从中国进口的海鲜&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/world/japan&quot;>;日本&lt;/a>;在北京针对其邻国的海产品实施禁令后，日本的股价暴跌&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/24/japan-begins-releasing-fukushima-wastewater-into-pacific-ocean&quot;>;福岛核电站废水排放&lt;/a>;第一核电站。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;公共广播公司 NHK 援引中国海关的数据称，8 月份进口额较去年同期下降 67%，至约 30 亿日元（合 2020 万美元）。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; p>; &lt;p>;北京和香港8月下旬决定暂停所有日本水产品进口，引发了外交争端，并引发了&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/”的反日情绪高涨mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/world/china&quot;>;中国&lt;/a>;，日本企业和外交机构收到大量&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment /2023/aug/28/japan-businesses-abusive-phone-calls-china-fukushima-waste-water&quot;>;辱骂电话&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/ span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/sep/04/state-backed-disinformation-fuelling-anger-in-china-over-fukushima-wastewater-japan&quot;>;国家-支持虚假信息，加剧中国对福岛水的愤怒&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists 的运营商/tag/environment/fukushima&quot;>;东京电力公司 (Tepco) 福岛核电站于 8 月 24 日开始向海中注入超过 100 万吨水，引起了中国和当地渔业社区的批评&lt;a href= “https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/24/they-wont-buy-it-fish-traders-anxious-after-fukushima-wastewater-release&quot;>;对其渔获物的声誉造成损害&lt; /a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这些水经过处理，去除了大部分放射性物质，但含有氚，一种氢的同位素，很难从水中分离出来。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;科学家指出，中国的自有核电站排放的废水&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/25/fukushima-daiichi-nuclear-power-plant-china-wastewater-release&quot;>;浓度更高氚&lt;/a>;比福岛核电站排放中发现的氚含量高，而且其含量均在不被认为对人类健康有害的范围内。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;东京电力和政府官员表示，排放过程将在至少 30 年 – 不会影响海洋环境或人类健康，因为严重稀释的水中含有的氚含量完全在安全水平之内，这与联合国核监督机构国际原子能机构 (IAEA) 最近的一份报告的调查结果相呼应.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;海鲜禁令直到上月底才生效，但最新数据表明它已经对出口产生了重大影响。数据显示，中国8月份进口了价值1.4902亿元人民币（合2043万美元）的日本海鲜。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;中国是日本最大的海鲜市场，对此次排放行为表示谴责，海关机构称此举存在“放射性污染”的风险食品安全”。中国外交部表示，这是“极其自私和不负责任的行为”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;英国和美国有&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/jul/14/欧盟对放水表示支持&lt;/a>;，欧盟赞扬日本当局在核废水排入海洋前几周“及时、透明地定期更新福岛状况”。韩国政府表示，尽管大部分韩国公众对安全存在担忧，但它接受国际原子能机构报告背后的科学依据。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;美国驻日本大使拉姆·伊曼纽尔 (Rahm Emanuel) 在他指责中国在实施海鲜禁令时使用“经济胁迫”，而中国自己的船只却继续在日本沿海捕鱼。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“经济胁迫是他们经济工具箱中最持久、最有害的工具，”伊曼纽尔说。上星期。 “中国现在在日本经济海域进行捕鱼，同时又对日本实施单方面禁运。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;作为回应，中国外交部表示伊曼纽尔应该停止鼓励日本的“不负责任”行为。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;东京在本月向世界贸易组织提交的一份文件中对该禁令提出抗议，称其“完全不可接受”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该禁令已经对日本企业产生了影响。日本，有报道称扇贝和其他海鲜堆积在北海道最北端主岛加工厂的冰柜中，北海道 64% 的海鲜出口到了中国。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;福岛的水在被污染后受到污染。用于冷却福岛第一核电站被 &lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/world/japan-earthquake-and- 击中后熔化的三个核反应堆海啸&quot;>;2011 年 3 月发生的强烈海啸&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 25 Sep 2023 13:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Matteo Messina Denaro, ‘last godfather’ of Sicilian mafia, dies after long illness, reports say]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/25/matteo-messina-denaro-last-godfather-of-sicilian-mafia-cosa-nostra-dies-after-long-illness]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-25T04:42:26Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/9b025da8aa02f5297e4a5d3e411ee328f9698a6e/0_640_2863_1718 /master/2863.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=a04cb8b187cd3ab583b9a0b7cd1fbfee&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Matteo Messina Denaro 于 1 月 16 日在巴勒莫被捕后的照片。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Matteo Messina据意大利媒体报道，西西里黑手党的“最后教父”德纳罗因长期患病而去世，他被指控策划了科萨·诺斯特拉 (Cosa Nostra) 犯下的一些最令人发指的罪行。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;1 月，德纳罗，61 岁，自 1993 年以来一直躲藏起来，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jan/16/italy-most-wanted-mafia-boss-matteo-messina-德纳罗被捕&quot;>;在巴勒莫的一家私人诊所被捕&lt;/a>;，他在那里以假名安德里亚·博纳菲德 (Andrea Bonafede) 定期接受肿瘤治疗。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;8 月，他被从” p>; &lt;p>;绰号 Diabolik 或 &lt;em>;U Siccu&lt;/em>;（瘦子），德纳罗于 1962 年出生于西西里岛的卡斯特尔韦特拉诺。他的父亲是一位有权势的科萨·诺斯特拉 (Cosa Nostra) 老板，德纳罗在家族企业中蓬勃发展，在废物、风能和零售领域建立一个价值数十亿欧元的非法帝国。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;2002 年，他因亲自杀害或下令谋杀数十人而被定罪并缺席判处终身监禁。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这名曾臭名昭著地声称：“我一个人填满了一座墓地”的歹徒在逃期间，显然一直保持着奢华的生活方式，这要归功于几位资助者，据检察官称，这些资助者包括：政治家和商人。他以穿着昂贵的西装、戴着劳力士和雷朋太阳镜而闻名。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;由于几乎完全没有近期照片，寻找德纳罗的任务变得很复杂。意大利当局仅利用 20 世纪 80 年代末和 90 年代初拍摄的几张身份照片，利用最新的计算机技术和 &lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com 提供的信息，以数字方式重建了他的外貌。 /international/lists/tag/world/mafia&quot;>;黑手党&lt;/a>;叛徒。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;7a064088ab77e18383c2969444f183fca89959d6&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co. uk/7a064088ab77e18383c2969444f183fca89959d6/6_0_737_442/500.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;警方发布的年轻德纳罗的合成图像和计算机生成的老年人图像。&quot; width=&quot;500&quot; height=&quot;300&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;警方发布的年轻德纳罗的合成图像和计算机生成的老年人图像。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;照片：美联社&lt;/多年来，已有数十人因身份错误而被逮捕。 2019 年，宪兵宪兵突击搜查西西里岛一家医院，逮捕了一名来自卡斯特尔韦特拉诺的男子，该男子正在神经科康复中。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;30 年来，每当调查人员似乎更接近目标时，德纳罗就会消失离开。就像幽灵一样，他会在世界各地消失并重新出现。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;逮捕前的周五，宪兵队收到了决定性的举报：1 月 16 日上午 8 点左右，嫌疑人将返回诊所接受检查。治疗。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/feb/02/like-being-on- a-rollercoaster-the-man-who-caught-sicilys-last-mafia-boss&quot;>;“就像坐过山车一样”：抓住了西西里岛最后一个黑手党老大的人&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt; p>;被捕后，德纳罗被转移到意大利中部城市拉奎拉的一所戒备森严的监狱，他在那里继续接受癌症治疗。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“你逮捕我只是因为我的病，”德纳罗与其他西西里黑手党头目一样，德纳罗一直拒绝与当局合作并揭露科萨诺斯特拉的罪行。据黑手党线人和检察官称，他掌握了西西里黑手党实施的一些最残暴谋杀案的关键，其中包括杀死传奇反黑手党治安官乔瓦尼·法尔科内和保罗·博尔塞利诺的炸弹袭击。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;调查人员现在担心西西里黑手党的最后一位教父已经将这些秘密带进了坟墓。&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx. net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; 目标=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 25 Sep 2023 12:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[No 10 increasingly concerned AI could be used to create bioweapons]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/sep/25/ai-bioweapons-rishi-sunak-safety]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-25T04:00:18Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/62090313f43554650a6091528f1fabdfca085cb3/0_987_6368_3823 /master/6368.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=13bf445a7f1ff239c5a2f3c5c1813506&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;官员们越来越担心这种可能性，以及需要通过监管来缓解这些可能性&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;随着唐宁街对下一代技术进步力量的担忧日益加深，对犯罪分子或恐怖分子可能利用人工智能造成大规模杀伤性的担忧将成为世界领导人峰会讨论的主要议题。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;英国官员在 11 月的人工智能安全峰会之前，他们正在世界各地巡演，希望就一份联合声明达成共识，该声明将警告流氓行为者利用该技术造成大规模死亡的危险。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;总理里希·苏纳克 (Rishi Sunak) 周围的人担心，这项技术很快就会强大到足以帮助个人制造生物武器或完全逃避人类控制。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;官员们越来越担心这种可能性，以及需要通过监管来缓解这些可能性在最近与高级技术主管讨论之后。 Last week, the scientist behind a landmark letter calling for a pause in developing powerful AI systems said tech executives &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/sep/21/ai-focused-tech-firms-locked-race-bottom-warns-mit-professor-max-tegmark&quot;>;privately agreed with the concept of a hiatus&lt;/a>; but felt they were locked into an AI arms race with rivals.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;One person briefed on the summit conversations said: “The point of the summit is going to be to warn about the risks of &#39;frontier AI&#39;, that&#39;s what Downing Street is focusing on most right now.” Frontier AI is a term used to refer to the most advanced AI models that could be dangerous enough to pose a risk to human life.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Sunak has been &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/may/26/rishi-sunak-races-to-tighten-rules-for-ai-amid-fears-of-existential-risk&quot;>;warning about&lt;/a>; the risks posed by AI for several months, urging the international community to adopt &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/may/18/uk-will-lead-on-guard-rails-to-limit-dangers-of-ai-says-rishi-sunak&quot;>;guard rails&lt;/a>; to prevent it being misused.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;On Friday, the deputy prime minister, Oliver Dowden, told world leaders at the UN general assembly: “Because tech companies and non-state actors often have country-sized influence and prominence in AI, this challenge requires a new form of multilateralism.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Officials have been alarmed by recent developments in AI models. Last year, an AI tool took just six hours &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theverge.com/2022/3/17/22983197/ai-new-possible-chemical-weapons-generative-models-vx&quot;>;to suggest&lt;/a>; 40,000 different potentially lethal molecules, some of which were similar to VX, the most potent nerve agent ever developed.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Earlier this year, researchers found ChatGPT &lt;a href=&quot;https://gizmodo.com/gpt4-open-ai-chatbot-task-rabbit-chatgpt-1850227471&quot;>;was able to lie to a human&lt;/a>; to achieve a specific goal. The AI chatbot persuaded a person to solve a “Captcha” tool designed to weed out robots online after telling the human that it was a person with a sight impairment who needed help to access a website.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Government sources worry that a criminal or terrorist could use AI to help them work out the ingredients for a bioweapon, before sending them to a robotic laboratory where they can be mixed and dispatched without any human oversight.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;That risk will soon increase exponentially, some believe, with companies already spending hundreds of millions of pounds on much more powerful processors to train the next generation of AI tools.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Another significant concern is the emergence of “artificial general intelligence”, a term that refers to an AI system that can autonomously perform any task at a human, or above-human, level – and could pose an existential risk to humans. There are fears that AGI is a matter of years away.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The existential AGI risk approach, however, has also been &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.dair-institute.org/about/&quot;>;criticised by AI experts&lt;/a>;, who argue that the threat is overstated, results in concerns such as disinformation being ignored and risks entrenching the power of leading tech companies by introducing regulation that excludes newcomers. Last week, a senior tech executive told US lawmakers that &lt;a href=&quot;https://viewer.gutools.co.uk/technology/2023/sep/12/us-senate-ai-hearings-microsoft-nvidia&quot;>;the concept of uncontrollable AGI&lt;/a>; was “science fiction”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Nevertheless, Sunak wants to use the summit to focus attention on existential risks, rather than the more immediate possibilities that AI could be used to create deepfake images, or could result in discriminatory outcomes if used to help make public policy decisions.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Benedict Macon-Cooney, the chief policy strategist at the Tony Blair Institute, which recently published a policy report on AI, said: “Biosecurity, autonomous weapons systems – these are things we have to make sure we get answers to. Many in the AI industry have told politicians these are real risks. Politicians have been posed the question, and they must come up with a response.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The prime minister is also being guided by what is diplomatically possible, sources say.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Several world leaders &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/sep/15/rishi-sunak-considers-banning-chinese-officials-from-half-of-ai-summit&quot;>;are due to attend the summit&lt;/a>;, including Canada&#39;s prime minister, Justin Trudeau, and the French president, Emmanuel Macron. The UK has invited China to attend, but is considering allowing officials from Beijing to attend only part of the summit, amid concern about Chinese espionage in western democracies.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;British officials have been touring the world in recent days to test the scope for some form of agreement at the end of the summit. The UK is keen to have a formal statement that leaders can sign afterwards, as well as a commitment to hold other such summits in future.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The best way to get an agreement among such a diverse range of countries, officials believe, is to focus on non-state actors, rather than trying to dictate how countries develop their own technology.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Downing Street is spending £100m on a new AI taskforce to help test algorithms as they are developed. British officials plan to use the summit to urge companies around the world to send their AI tools to the UK for assessment before rolling them out more widely.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Dowden said on Friday: “Only nation states can provide reassurance that the most significant national security concerns have been allayed.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;A government spokesperson said AI has “enormous potential to change every aspect of our lives” and the Frontier AI taskforce had been established to ensure the technology is developed safely and responsibly, with the AI safety summit also looking at “a range of possible risks”.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 25 Sep 2023 12:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Russian news outlet in Latvia believes European state behind phone hack]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/25/latvia-russia-meduza-phone-hack-galina-timchenko]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-25T04:00:18Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/27ca62ce6b636a6c1af265fe1f67461603d91964/0_262_4173_2504/master/4173.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=54b5836ef0ff705d498dfa2aa9278676&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Dressed in winter coats, a group of white, mostly young people stand outside next to a leafless tree, holding signs, including of fashioned to make Vladimir Putin look like Adolf Hitler. In the center, a young man holds a young woman, who is crying.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;An independent Russian news outlet whose founder was hacked in Germany earlier this year through military-grade spyware has said it believes a European state was most likely &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/sep/13/exiled-russian-journalist-galina-timchenko-reportedly-hacked-using-nso-group-spyware&quot;>;behind the cyberattack&lt;/a>;, raising thorny questions about an EU member state&#39;s possible use of a blacklisted cyberweapon against a journalist.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Galina Timchenko and Ivan Kolpakov, the founder and current editor-in-chief of Meduza, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/media/2023/jan/26/russia-outlaws-meduza-in-attempt-to-stamp-out-independent-news&quot;>;a Latvia-based independent Russian news outlet outlawed by the Kremlin&lt;/a>;, said new circumstantial evidence pointed to an EU state as the likely perpetrator behind the hacking of Timchenko&#39;s mobile phone in Berlin earlier this year, which occurred in February shortly before she participated in a meeting of exiled Russian journalists.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The news prompted one European member of parliament to say it seemed that governments were increasingly using surveillance methods comparable to those once deployed by the East German secret police, the Stasi, without proper oversight.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/17/berlin-prosecutor-probes-possible-poisoning-of-russian-journalist&quot;>;Berlin prosecutor investigates possible poisoning of Russian journalist&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;Timchenko was first alerted to the hack when she received a warning from Apple. The Guardian has since learned that at least four other Russian journalists – three of whom have mobile phones based in Latvia – received the same warning.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;An investigation by the Citizen Lab at the University of Toronto and Access Now later confirmed with a high degree of certainty that Timchenko&#39;s phone – which uses a Latvian country code – was hacked by a government user of Pegasus, a sophisticated spyware made by Israel&#39;s NSO Group. When successfully deployed, Pegasus can hack any phone, and even turn a mobile into a remote listening device.&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;709b7e2830628c6d656c2bb1e3d21d7063723210&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/709b7e2830628c6d656c2bb1e3d21d7063723210/0_28_2855_1713/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;A close shot of a middle-aged white woman wearing dark sunglasses and with chin-length brown hair and bangs.&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;Galina Timchenko, the CEO of Meduza, speaks during an interview outside a court building in Moscow on 8 June 2019.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Tatyana Makeyeva/Reuters&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;Timchenko initially said she believed the attack against her had originated in Russia, pointing to ways in which the Kremlin has pursued and stalked her and colleagues at Meduza since 2014, including using sophisticated cyberattacks.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;But researchers at the Citizen Lab and Access Now have said they do not believe Russia is a client of NSO. The independent researchers have also confirmed that agencies within Latvia, Estonia and Germany are clients of NSO Group and have access to the spyware.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Timchenko – who has lived in Latvia for nearly a decade – said she now believes that an EU state may have targeted her in the hopes of capturing information from exchanges she has had with other Russian journalists who have more recently left Russia. In any case, she called it an “expensive pleasure” for any state to have targeted her.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Timchenko and Kolpakov point to tensions that emerged late last year when Meduza was the first Latvia-based outlet to publicly defend another independent Russian media group, the liberal-leaning broadcaster TV Rain, which was expelled from the Baltic country after &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/dec/06/rain-russian-tv-station-in-latvia-loses-licence-over-ukraine-war-coverage&quot;>;a state broadcasting regulator accused it of being a threat to Latvian national security.&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The broadcaster was criticised for displaying a map of Russia that included occupied Crimea, and for one anchor&#39;s decision to refer to Russian troops as “our army”. TV Rain also did not provide viewers with Latvian subtitles, as required. The broadcaster was forced to move its operations to the Netherlands, and stoked what press reports at the time called a &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.reuters.com/business/media-telecom/latvia-cancels-license-russian-independent-television-station-tv-rain-2022-12-06/&quot;>;growing rift between the Latvian majority and Russian-speaking minority in Latvia&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The Meduza journalists said they published &lt;a href=&quot;https://meduza.io/en/feature/2022/12/06/meduza-s-statement-regarding-the-revocation-of-tv-rain-s-latvian-broadcasting-license&quot;>;an open letter of support&lt;/a>; for press freedom, which was critical of the Latvian decision and signed by 300 supporters. It called the regulator&#39;s move “unfair, wrong, and disproportionate to the official violations”.&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;9548bf037db0ccb4005a867e919b9530a0ab1d17&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/9548bf037db0ccb4005a867e919b9530a0ab1d17/0_182_3500_2101/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;A photo taken in a large interior room with a low ceiling and neat wooden rafters, florescent lights, gray industrial carpeting, and large wooden tables. A black raincoat hangs on a wooden post, and a black umbrella is open in the foreground. Two white men appear to chat, one seated at one of the desks and the other standing alongside it. &quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;Journalists work in the independent, Russia-focused Meduza office in Riga, Latvia, on 30 March 2015.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Ints Kalniņš/Reuters&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;While the letter described TV Rain&#39;s violations as “wrong”, it also praised the Russian outlet in exile as one of the “few truly independent media outlets” that had retained a large audience inside Russia. The network, Meduza said, was obviously anti-Kremlin and opposed to the invasion of Ukraine.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“We published this letter and for the very first time, Latvian journalists supported us as well,” Timchenko said. It also prompted some criticism of her own organisation.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;It is this criticism that the journalists see as possibly prompting Latvian authorities or others to home in on Meduza as a target of surveillance.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Now it is likely that the hack was operated by some European security service. We don&#39;t know if it was Latvia or some other country, but we have more [presence] in Latvia,” said Kolpakov.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Neither Latvia nor Germany – where the hack occurred – have offered to investigate the breach, which was widely reported.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The Biden administration has blacklisted NSO and other spyware companies, calling them a threat to US national security. In response to questions from the Guardian about the hacking of Timchenko, a US state department spokesperson said it condemned the harassment or extrajudicial surveillance of journalists, and stood in solidarity with independent Russian journalists “who work to shine a light on the Kremlin&#39;s brutal war against Ukraine”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Latvia has generally cultivated a strong reputation for protecting press freedoms. A 2022 state department report on human rights found “no credible reports” that the government monitored private online communications without appropriate legal authority.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Latvia&#39;s embassy in Washington said in a statement that Meduza&#39;s work providing “objective information to Russian audiences worldwide” was “widely appreciated in Latvia”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“The [Foreign] Ministry is not aware of any electronic surveillance measures being taken against Ms Timchenko,” the embassy said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;It added: “Latvia has been providing a safe haven for independent Russian media and their staff. More than 20 different media institutions from Russia currently operate from Latvia.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;A spokesperson for the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.dw.com/en/german-police-secretly-bought-nso-pegasus-spyware/a-59113197&quot;>;German federal police (BKA)&lt;/a>;, which became an NSO customer in 2019, said it would not provide information about capabilities or tools used in covert measures.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The development followed a months-long inquiry by &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/may/09/eu-parliament-report-calls-for-tighter-regulation-of-spyware&quot;>;a special committee of the European parliament&lt;/a>; into spyware abuses by European governments, including in Hungary, Spain, Greece and Poland.&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;29ba18c5d69b8434f0f1772120334172b002303b&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/29ba18c5d69b8434f0f1772120334172b002303b/0_15_4567_2742/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;A white woman with long, thick, curly reddish-brown hair wearing round tortoiseshell glasses and a blue pinstripe suits appears to be listening to someone as she stands behind a microphone at a lectern, with a bright blue background behind her.&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;Sophie in &#39;t Veld, a Dutch member of the European Parliament, in Brussels, Belgium, 8 November 2022.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Olivier Hoslet/EPA&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;Sophie in &#39;t Veld, a Dutch European parliament member who has headed the probe, expressed dismay at the recent developments and the apparent use of “totalitarian tactics” inside EU states, which she said were continuing to use Pegasus and other spyware tools without any intervention or oversight by national governments or the European Commission.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“People have often said this whole spyware story compares to the European version of Watergate. It&#39;s not. It&#39;s more like &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n3_iLOp6IhM&quot;>;The Lives of Others&lt;/a>;,” she said, referring to the Oscar-winning German film depicting the pervasive surveillance of artists and writers in East Germany in the 1980s.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/sep/13/exiled-russian-journalist-galina-timchenko-reportedly-hacked-using-nso-group-spyware&quot;>;Exiled Russian journalist hacked using NSO Group spyware&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“I&#39;m not saying Europe is already descending into totalitarianism, but these are totalitarian methods,” she said. “If it is true that the Latvian government or other European states did this, then there is no way to find out. There is no remedy, and no oversight.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;She added: “[EU] governments are using it for political purposes, just like undemocratic ones do. In some very exceptional cases the use of spyware might be legitimate … the point is that we have no way of knowing if the use is proportionate and legitimate.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;A person familiar with the issue said NSO has opened an investigation into the matter. The company has said in the past that it only sells its powerful hacking tools to government agencies for the purpose of investigating serious crimes.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 25 Sep 2023 12:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Brian Cox on Rupert Murdoch’s succession plan: ‘the freedom to manipulate’]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2023/sep/25/brian-cox-rupert-murdoch-news-corp-exit-comment-joke-succession]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-25T02:49:46Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/cd05f964171745f9fcc519cc5ac97313bc56e445/0_0_2500_1500/master/2500.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=057a64e8cb3063a86e34fef767950e08&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Brian Cox and Rupert Murdoch&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Succession actor Brian Cox has commented on Rupert Murdoch&#39;s &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/media/2023/sep/21/rupert-murdoch-stepping-down-chair-fox-news-corp&quot;>;own succession plan&lt;/a>; while seemingly criticising the media mogul for imposing his worldview on other people.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Cox told the BBC he thought Murdoch may have spent too much time watching the HBO hit series that draws heavily on real-life dramas within the Murdoch dynasty.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Golden Globe winner Cox, who portrays family patriarch Logan Roy in the series, said on the weekend that &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/media/2023/sep/21/rupert-murdoch-fox-news-lawsuits-donald-trump&quot;>;Murdoch&#39;s announcement&lt;/a>; that he would be stepping down as chair of News Corp and Fox to make way &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/media/2023/sep/22/what-does-lachlan-murdoch-succession-rupert-mean-news-corp-australia&quot;>;for his eldest son&lt;/a>; was not surprising.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I think he&#39;s been watching too much Succession, clearly,” Cox said of Murdoch&#39;s decision to anoint Lachlan over his siblings Elisabeth and James.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/media/2023/sep/23/rupert-murdoch-made-his-own-rules-what-is-the-media-moguls-real-legacy&quot;>;Rupert Murdoch made his own rules – what is the media mogul&#39;s real legacy?&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“He&#39;s probably the most tenacious human on God&#39;s earth. He&#39;s just kept on going but I think eventually there comes a point when he has to stop and it had to happen and it&#39;s happened.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Cox said he suspected Rupert Murdoch&#39;s mental health at 92 was “pretty good … but the workload must be too much now”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The actor was critical of Murdoch&#39;s interpretation of press freedom, however, responding to the media boss&#39;s statement last week when he said: “The battle for the freedom of speech and, ultimately, the freedom of thought, has never been more intense. My father [Keith Murdoch] firmly believed in freedom and Lachlan is absolutely committed to the cause.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Cox took issue with Murdoch&#39;s “generalised” statement.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Freedom? Freedom for what? Freedom to impose his ideas on other people, freedom to kind of manipulate certain things in certain directions? I mean, he&#39;s certainly done a lot of that in his life,” he told the BBC.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Cox said his Succession character differed from Murdoch in a crucial way – the fictional mogul is self-made while the real-life latter inherited and built on his father&#39;s empire. But, he said, both were “very conniving” to achieve their own ends.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The septuagenarian actor, who is &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2023/sep/20/brian-cox-bach-theatre-the-score&quot;>;currently in rehearsals&lt;/a>; for the Theatre Royal Bath&#39;s production of Oliver Cotton&#39;s The Score (Cox will play Johann Sebastian Bach), declined to offer an opinion on whether Lachlan was “Kendall, Roman or Connor”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I&#39;m not sure which one he is because I kind of keep out of the whole Murdoch thing.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Because when you play a role, it&#39;s your creation. The one thing that there is in common is how little Rupert actually expresses himself and he allows things [actions] to speak for itself.”&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 25 Sep 2023 11:52:02 +0800</pubDate></item></channel></rss>